Aspire currently only supports static Dockerfile paths and contents via WithDockerfile. To enable scenarios where the Dockerfile needs to be generated at runtime (e.g., based on model state or environment), introduce new overloads for WithDockerfile that accept both sync and async callbacks to produce Dockerfile contents.

- Add overloads:

```C#
public static IResourceBuilder<T> WithDockerfile<T>(this IResourceBuilder<T> builder, string contextPath, Func<string> dockerfileFactory, string? stage = null) where T : ContainerResource;
public static IResourceBuilder<T> WithDockerfile<T>(this IResourceBuilder<T> builder, string contextPath, Func<DockerFileFactoryContext, CancellationToken, Task<string>> dockerfileFactory, string? stage = null) where T : ContainerResource;
```

```C#
public class DockerFileFactoryContext
{
    public IServiceProvider Services { get; init; }
}
```

```diff
public class DockerfileBuildAnnotation(string contextPath, string dockerfilePath, string? stage) : IResourceAnnotation
{
    public string ContextPath => contextPath;
    public string DockerfilePath => dockerfilePath;
    public string? Stage => stage;
    public Dictionary<string, object?> BuildArguments { get; } = [];
    public Dictionary<string, object> BuildSecrets { get; } = [];
+   public Func<CancellationToken, Task<string>> DockerFileFactory { get; init; }
}
```

- The callback should be invoked once at build graph materialization time, and the output written to a resource-specific path (avoid conflicts).
- Trust the callback's output (no content validation).
- Update all consumers of DockerfileBuildAnnotation to support the callback and generated file path:
  - DcpExecutor
  - ManifestPublishingContext
  - AzurePublishingContext
  - DockerComposePublishingContext
  - KubernetesPublishingContext
- Provide XML doc comments and documentation for the new overloads.

